Everything downstream should know how tests here validate the CLI: they treat `dispatch(&fs, &cli, &mut out)` as the single entry point and drive it entirely through `clap`-parsed argv plus a `FakeFs` stand-in for the real filesystem, never touching parsing or storage logic directly.

This constrains any change to the CLI surface: adding, renaming, or changing flags on a subcommand (`add-task`, `delete-task`, `list`) must be reflected in the corresponding test's argv construction, and changing output formatting (the `"added: …"`, `"deleted: …"`, or `"| id | task | … |"` line formats) breaks the assertions here even if the underlying data model is untouched. The `Fs` trait is the seam between dispatch logic and actual I/O — any new dispatch behavior that reads or writes files must go through `Fs`, or `FakeFs` in tests can't observe it, and `StatusError::Io`/`StatusError::TaskIdNotFound` are the two error variants tests currently assert on, so new failure modes need corresponding coverage here.

No `mod.rs` or dispatch-implementation `.ctx` was supplied alongside this one, so the actual `dispatch`, `Cli`, and `Fs` definitions live in a sibling file not summarized here — consult it before changing argv shape or output strings.